### ✅ What is HTTP Parameter Pollution?

HTTP Parameter Pollution (HPP) occurs when an attacker manipulates URL parameters to inject malicious data. For example:

- `https://example.com/login?username=admin&password=123` is fine.
- `https://example.com/login?username=admin&password=123&username=malicious` may cause the server to interpret the second `username` as a parameter override.

This can be used to bypass input validation if the server is not properly handling parameter order or duplicates.

